      • validateUpgrade

        public void validateUpgrade(@Nonnull
                            ExecutionStep<?> to)
        Description copied from interface: ExecutionStep
        Checks whether or not this execution step can be safely replaced with other without causing upgrade issues such as corrupted state stores or repartition topics.

        validateUpgrade checks compatibility by starting from the parent and then traversing down the execution step tree. This means that at any given point, the implementation can assume that the path above the current node is upgrade compatible.

        The implementation relies on two different types of nodes:

        1. Enforcing Steps: these steps are "stopping" points in the validation tree and will bring the to tree to match the enforcing step, skipping any passive steps that show up in between./li>
        2. Passive Steps: these are steps that can be added/removed to topologies without causing any issues to upgrades. They will delegate their upgrade validation to their corresponding source nodes

        With this implementation strategy, we essentially have two pointers into query plans: the source and the target. We traverse the trees advancing the pointer in the source tree until we hit an enforcing step. The enforcing step will advance the pointer until either the target tree has a matching, valid enforcing step or there is an invalid step in between at which point an exception will be propagated.

        For example, consider the following two trees: 

           source (s): SINK -> SELECT -> SELECT_KEY -> SOURCE
   target (t): SINK -> FILTER -> SELECT_KEY -> SOURCE
        Within these trees, the SINK, SELECT_KEY and SOURCE nodes are enforcing steps and the others are passive steps. The algorithm would first compare the two SINK steps, then advance s until the s.SELECT_KEY step. Since t.FILTER is passive, it can be skipped, at which point the algorithm would hit another enforcing node (t.SELECT_KEY). It would then compare those two steps and the two SOURCE steps to determine whether or not the two trees are compatible. This essentially "reduces" the two trees only to their enforcing nodes and makes sure that those are compatible with one another.

        The default implementation does not support upgrades, taking an "allowlist" approach instead of a "denylist" approach so that we can guarantee that only query upgrades that we've reasoned about and stamped with an approval will be supported.

        Parameters:
        to - the execution step to upgrade to
